"Hedrack"
"acode trigger init"
"@eDESCRIPTION@n
The functions set_rflag(), remove_rflag(), set_dflag(), and remove_dflag() are
problematic, because each room has only one copy of each flag.  If your
softcode alters these flags, and the area gets saved to disk afterward, the
altered value of the flag will be saved...  and will be the flag's value after
a MUD reboot.  This does NOT concern the status and reset flags, which are
automatically set by the hardcode.

Example: you have a dark room, and elsewhere is an acode for a switch that
sets the \"Lit\" rflag in the dark room.  Since the switch starts out \"not
flipped\", you want the dark room to be dark after a MUD reboot.  If the area
gets saved to disk (because of modifications) after the switch has been
flipped, the next time the MUD reboots, that room will start out lit.

The original approach was to have two sets of rflags and dflags for every room
and door.  The 'init' acode trigger is a better approach.  You can simply have
an \"init\" trigger in the dark room, that removes the \"Lit\" rflag.

The init trigger gets called after all rooms are loaded from disk, but NO
RESETS have yet been done.  The room's status flags will all be set, but the
reset flags will have whatever value they had when last saved.  This means
that any objects you load to the room will be removed by the first reset
(unless they are no_reset, etc.)
"
""
