"area checklist"
"Here's a list of things you need to get a zone into the game:

@eGet your concept approved by Nereus@n
Self-explanatory.  Just drop me a mail or catch me when I'm on.

@eIdentify possible placement locations@n
I'd like to make sure new zones are sufficiently far away from existing areas
to prevent future overlap and overcrowding.  When you consider your area,
please also consider potential location.  Make sure to consider roads leading
to your area and possible transitional terrains, if necessary.  You may also
want to consider checking the jobs board to see if anyone else shares your
idea for a zone or is already working on a potential road or terrain
transition to a location you can place your area.

@eAdd your current work to the jobs board@n
Please add a quick note explaining what you are working on and any other
relevant information you'd like others to keep track of.

@eMap zone and exits@n
While mapping out your zone, ensure that you're not creating overlap.  You
might consider setting terrain types and exit sizes now, although some prefer
to do this later.

@eWrite rooms, extras, and codes@n
Ensure all rooms in the zone have extras and flavor acodes added.  Every room
should have extras, unless there are no_show objects for everything that can
be represented as an object - this should be extremely unlikely.

Dynamic things in rdescs - weather, light, mobs, sounds, smells, and so on -
need to be represented with acodes.  Be liberal with search acodes - don't
just have search codes in rooms where something pops.

That doesn't mean you need to have an acode in every single room, but don't be
afraid to use them for things you think people might try.

@eWrite mobs and add their resets@n
These steps don't have to be in any particular order - some people write the
whole zone first, and some write the mobs and then the room descriptions.

Have a look through help mob_check_list for specifics on what you need to
remember for each mob.

@eWrite objects and add their resets in the zone@n
Again, this step doesn't have to be done in any particular order.

For items in the room description, consider adding objects in the room that
players can interact with.  Is there a table or other furniture?  Big boulders
or plants that might be interesting?  Add an item for them.

@eWrite helpfile for the zone@n
All areas should have a helpfile associated with them.  Write a help file with
the area name, and rset the help file to match the name of the help file
you've created.

@eCheck your spelling@n
The spelling in all your rooms and room extras can be checked with the command
\"roomlist -S\" while standing somewhere in the area.

@eSubmit zone for approval@n
This can be a frustrating step since you're ready for your zone to open, but
it's better to catch issues before players find a loophole that you forgot
about and we have to track down items and remove them from the game.

Send a mail to Nereus - I'll make sure that the appropriate people review your
zone.  Please leave all rbugs in the zone until it's been opened, so if there
are multiple reviewers they can see what comments have already been left.

The mail should contain the following:
- Vnum of the first room in the zone and any notes pertinent to the entire zone.
- Vnum of every mob and object created or loading in the zone.

Once the zone has been reviewed and any issues are closed, mark the zone's
status to open and post an announcement note.
