"aset"
"@eSYNTAX@n

aset                       : shows the current action's stats
aset <field> <value>       : set action flags

@WPARAMETERS:@n

Fields that can be set are:
Trigger: what triggers the acode being edited
Value: used for random or time-based triggers
Command: used to set specific trigger commands
Target: used to set specific targets of the Command Field

Using aset without a field will function in the same mannar as astat.

Using aset <field> without a value will show all values available for that
field.

@eDESCRIPTION@n

To access the aset command, you must first used aedit to target an acode in
the room you are in.  See @Whelp aedit@n for more information on that command.
See also the @Whelp aflag@n file for additional relevant info.

The aset command is used to set the high level values of acode.  These values
determine what triggers the acode.  Not all the fields have to be set, in
fact, certain fields aren't even active or useful without other fields being
set correctly.

For example:
aset trigger entering room - will trigger the code when someone enters.
or
aset trigger searching - will trigger the code when someone has search on.
but
aset trigger random - will require the use of the value field to set how often
the random action is triggered.  Values range from 0-1000 with 1000 being
every tick.

Acodes with the Trigger set to none can only be called from another acode
or with some combination of the command and target fields are also filled.
Both fields can contain multiple options, separated by spaces.
For Example:
aset command 1 open move 2 lift
aset target lid top
would trigger the code with any of the following commands:
open lid, open top, move lid, move top, lift lid, or lift top.

The 1 open in the Command field means the character triggering the acode only
needs 1 letter of the word open to trigger it.  In this case \"o lid\", \"op
lid\", oe \"ope lid\" will have the same effects as \"open lid\".

For commands that appear in the \"Command\" table, it's best not to specify a
minimum required string length.  If you don't the number will default to the
number of characters needed for the command to be recognized on the command
line.  So in the example above, the command should be \"open move 2 lift\",
since \"open\" and \"move\" are in the command table.

@WRETURNS:@n

none

@WEXAMPLES:@n

The possible combinations are too numerous to reasonably list examples.  Read
through the description and take a look at various rooms with triggered
actions in them to see the variety and what results from those settings.

See Also: help triggers
"
