"Astronomy"
"@eSYNTAX@n

moon_phase( )        : returns the current moon phase.
                         -1 - the moon is not up
                          0 - full
                          1 - waning gibbous
                          2 - waning half
                          3 - waning crescent
                          4 - new (invisible)
                          5 - waxing crescent
                          6 - waxing half
                          7 - waxing gibbous

@eBACKGROUND@n

The @emoon@n revolves around the earth every 39,343 minutes, or about 27.32
days--its @esidereal period@n.  During this time, however, the earth moves on
its path around the sun, so it takes a little longer for the moon to cycle
through its phases...  The moon's @esynodic period@n is about 29.53 days.

A @enew moon@n occurs when the moon is on the same side of the earth as the
sun, and cannot be seen since the far side of the moon is illuminated by the
sun.  A @efull moon@n is seen when the moon is on the opposite side of the
earth as the sun.

The rising and setting times of the moon vary greatly, since the full moon is
always highest around midnight, and the new moon, though unseen, is always
highest around noon.  Also, the moon's path wanders north and south of the
equator.

On this MUD, the moon's zenith gets 49 minutes later each day (a synodic
period of about 29.39 days), and its rise and set times vary according to a
sinusoidal curve, centered around 12 hours visibility time, with the moon's
sidereal period.  The maximum is 16 hours, the minimum is 8 hours.  These
numbers are all gross approximations of the Earth moon, but should be good
enough for a MUD.

The values returned by moon_phase( ) are approximate; since the synodic period
is over 29 days, each phase will last for 3-4 days.
"
