"Build Process"
"@eTHE CURRENT PROBLEM@n

Several of us discovered at once that an item, the rune stones, had been in
game on a relatively low-level mob.  (level 10 mob had an 89% chance of having
a rune stone each spawn) As far as any of us could tell, these were meant to
go with a level 60-80 weapon that never went live.  Granted, they alone don't
cause any harm but an item that buffs up a potentially 60-80 weapon on a level
10 mob, if the weapon was ever put in players would have a way over-balanced
start.  A brief review showed no one knew it had gone live, that it had been
live for quite some time, and that it shouldn't have been.

Now, the above issue, while pertinent, isn't as important as the issue at hand
which is that some things are going live without a complete and sensible
review.  New zones go live after a rough review process and that helps
immensely but could still be firmed up a little more.  New items and mobs
going into existing live zones currently has no review process and holds the
potential for some very bad results.  The problem is then that these things
need to be revised and dealt with.

Side comment, its not particularly my place Talis to implement new
procedures.  That's basically the Demigod's job.  I offer my apologies to Orb
if this is stepping on her toes but I know she's unavailable right now and she
can readily enough modify or remove any plans I come up with.  In the mean
time, I'm just presenting a draft guideline I feel (as do a majority of imms
available) will benefit the build process.


@eTHE BUILD PROCESS - REVISED@n

@GNEW ZONES@n

@b*@n The description, general plot purpose, and guideline for new zones should
be discussed with an Architect (see help powers) before it is begun.  Once
approved, building may begin.

@b*@n All new zones should be reviewed before going live.  A Reviewer (see
help powers) or Architect, or someone appointed by an Architect, may review
the zone prior to it going live.  Once all revisions required are made and an
Architect gives final approval the zone may be flagged open.

@b*@n When submitting a zone for review, please try to have a list of all new
mobs and new items being added for the reviewer.  It helps ensure nothing new
will be missed.

@GNEW MOBS/ITEMS IN EXISTING LIVE ZONES@n

@b*@n All new items and mobs should be reviewed with the same quality that a
new zone is reiewed.  A Reviewer, Architect, or someone appointed by an
Architect should review any new items or mobs before they are added.

@b*@n New mobs/items going into a live zone need to be placed with care.  All
such changes should be discussed with the Architect.  If the immortal who
created the zone or who is currently in charge of it (if any) is available,
they also should have a say in the matter.


This is a work in progress, feedback is not only welcomed, it is encouraged. 
By the way, let me also add while I am the Architect in charge at this time,
this is in no way a bid for personal power.  I don't want anyone thinking I'm
just coming up with all this to try and take control of the mud.  In fact, I'd
probably be happier just being oblivious and going about my way building and
all the tasks that an Architect is supposed to be doing will greatly sap what
time I hae to build.  ;) Fortunately, I've also been thrust into enough
administratie type rolls to know I can do this and I'd personally much rather
see it done then left as vague as its been before.  I also do this with the
backing of as many immortals as are available currently to offer feedback.  If
anyone has problems with this, please speak up (Particularly Orb as the
Demigod).  My main goal is to keep things sane and organized.  Things aren't
critically bad or anything but everyone seems to agree a bit more organization
in the build process is needed and this seems to be the first step.
"
