"Cast_spell"
"@CSYNTAX@n

cast_spell( spell, char, target[, level[, speed]] )

@b@WPARAMETERS:@n

spell - Name of spell to cast
char - Pointer to character casting spell
target - The target of the spell: a character or object
level - optional casting level of the spell
speed - optional casting speed of the spell

@eRETURNS@n

An integer:
  0 if the casting failed.
  1 if the casting sequence has begun.

@b@W@CDESCRIPTION@n:@n

Causes char to cast spell on target.

There are a number of reasons why cast_spell() might fail and return 0:
  - Null caster.
  - Caster isn't standing, or is silenced, entangled, drowning, etc.
  - Bad target for the specified spell.
  - Spell can't be cast in the current room.

If the skill argument is omitted or zero, the spell is cast with the caster's
skill level.

The speed argument causes the casting steps to proceed as if the spell were
cast at that skill level...  the higher the level, the quicker the casting
occurs.  If you omit the speed argument, the specified (or default) casting
level is used.

The actual casting delays, in sixteenths of seconds, are:

cast_spell() to first spell.action:
  delay = max( 5, 10 - speed/2 )
  (that is, a minimum of 5/16 second)

spell.action to next spell.action:
  delay = 35 - speed

@b@WEXAMPLES:@n

cast_spell( slay, mob, victim );  // Causes mob to cast slay spell on victim
"
