"Dflag"
"@CSYNTAX@n
dflag        : displays the flags for a door
dflag <flag> : toggles the specified flag

(functions)
dflag( dflag, exit ) : returns the value of a dflag on an exit
set_dflag( dflag, exit ) : toggles the value of a dflag to true on one side of an exit
remove_dflag( dflag, exit ) : toggles the value of a dflag

@CDESCRIPTION@n
This is used to set a door to secret, locked and similar.  No_show can
not be found by searching while secret will sometimes be noticed by the
player.  To specify door for dflag to act on use dedit.

The set_flag() and remove_dflag() functions operate on only one side of an
exit.  The dflag command, however, works on both sizes by default.

Command options:
1 - set the flag for only one side

Some useful dflags:
Plural - messages refer to plural doors, e.g.  \"The wooden double doors are
closed.\"
No.Scan - scanning through the exit will show \"unknown\", regardless of whether
any creatures are there or not.  Far-scan will not proceed beyond a no.scan
exit.
No.Pass - the pass_door affect won't allow passage through the door, for those
levels 92 and under.
No.Blink - the blink spell will not consider this exit.
No.Path - will be excluded from path() results.

@CEXAMPLES@n
// Returns 1 if you can't flee north from this room
dflag( no.flee, door( room, north ) );

// toggles the no.flee flag on the north exit to true
set_dflag( no.flee, door( room, north ) );

// toggles the no.flee flag on the north exit to false
remove_dflag( no.flee, door( room, north ) );

// Sets the no.scan dflag on both sides
exit = door( room, north );
set_dflag( no.scan, exit );
set_dflag( no.scan, reverse( exit ) );
