@eDESCRIPTION@n

The dictionary command uses the standard editor commands to set up a list of
custom words that should not be considered erroneously spelled.

Enter as many words on each line as you like.

See also: help editor.
"
"@eIMMORTAL NOTES@n

dictionary -c             : list the custom dictionary
dictionary -c <string>    : search custom dictionary for words starting with string
dictionary -ca <word> ... : add word to custom dictionary
dictionary -cr <word> ... : remove word from custom dictionary

The \"dictionary -c\" commands manipulate a MUD-wide custom dictionary for words
that aren't found in the \"standard\" English dictionary.  This dictionary holds
TFE-specific terms that aren't found in the tables, for example names of
rivers like \"Elhanni\", or non-dictionary terms like \"shuvana\" and \"mithril\".

dictionary -s <string>    : search system dictionary for words starting with string
dictionary -sa <word> ... : add word to system dictionary
dictionary -sr <word> ... : remove word from system dictionary

The \"dictionary -s\" commands manipulate the \"system\" dictionary of standard
English words.  @eDo not@n add or remove entries to or from this dictionary
without verifying whether the word exists using www.dictionary.com.

dictionary -p <player>    : snoop player's dictionary.
                            requires snoop permissions.

@eDICTIONARY USAGE@n

When adding a @enoun@n to a dictionary, make sure you add the plural form.  For
example, if the noun is \"thing\", be sure to add \"things\".  Do NOT add
possessives like \"thing's\" or \"things'\", since the spelling checker
automatically checks the root word when it encounters these.

Proper nouns must be capitalized in the dictionary.  Do NOT add proper nouns
that are also non-proper nouns, e.g.  Stone (as someone's last name) or
Tombstone (as a town's name).

When adding a @everb@n to a dictionary, make sure you add all the additional
forms.  For example, if the verb is \"push\", be sure to add:
@Ipushed, pushing, pushes
@Ipusher, pushers (but NOT pusher's or pushers')
@Ipushy, pushiness, pushier, pushiest, pushily

Of course, not all of these forms will apply to all possible verbs.

Hyphenated and abbreviated words are supported, e.g.:
@Icul-de-sac, hocus-pocus, e.g., etc., i.e.
"
