"Expressions"
"Expressions in acodes, mprogs, and oprogs use a syntax that resembles the C
programming language.  Specifically, each expression consists of one or more
@eterms@n, concatenated with @eoperators@n.

@eTERMS@n

A term can be any of the following:

@Ivariable name
@I@Ii, ch, room, etc., see @ehelp variables@n.
@Iconstant value
@I@Ispell name, player race, skill name, etc.
@Icharacter string
@I@I\"literal string\", #data_name.
@Ifunction call
@I@Ifunction_name( arguments )
@Inon-negative decimal integer
@I@I0, 1, 536, etc.
@Inon-negative hexadecimal integer
@I@I0xff, 0xabcd1234, 0XFEDC, etc.
@Ia dice-roll specification
@I@I2d10, 5d3+2, etc.
@I( <expression> )

A term that evaluates to an integer value (literal integer, integer variable
like \"i\", function that returns an integer) may be preceded with '-', thus
negating its value.  Alternately, any term may be preceded by '!', which
performs a logical negation.  '~' performs bitwise negation.

For all bitwise operators, assume integers are 32-bit variables.  For
arithmetic operators, overflow from positive to negative occurs when an
integer is incremented past (2^31)-1.

@eOPERATORS@n

Multiple terms in an expression are separated by operators, which are listed
below in order of decreasing precedence.  Operators listed on the same line
have equal precedence, and are evaluated from left to right in the expression.

@I*, /, %         : integer multiply, divide, remainder.
@I+, -            : integer add, subtract
@I<<, >>          : bitwise left shift, right shift
@I<, >, <=, >=    : integer comparison
@I==, !=          : equals, not equals
@I\\&              : bitwise AND
@I\\^              : bitwise XOR (exclusive-or)
@I\\|              : bitwise OR
@I&&              : logical AND
@I||              : logical OR

Note that the expression \"short circuiting\" behavior of languages like C is
performed for the \"&&\" and \"||\" operators.  If the left-side term evaluates to
false (for \"&&\") or true (for \"||\"), the right-hand term is never evaluated.

For example, depending on the value of \"i\", the attack() function might not
get called in the following statements:

if( i == 1 && attack( mob, victim, 1d8, +raking claws\" ) ) { ... }
if( i == 1 || attack( mob, victim, 1d8, +raking claws\" ) ) { ... }

See also: variables, functions.
"
