"Gsp_guidelines"
"The purpose of this help file is to have a general guideline on hand to help
determine what is and is not considered unacceptable material and behavior
here.

Use of foul language or explicit content is acceptable in private between two
people (tells) to whatever extent they are comfortable.  The same goes for
clan channel chat.  If no one is complaining then consider it acceptable.

There should be a distinction between in-game content and out-of-game content.
The line can get a bit fuzzy so use your best judgement.  A person playing a
vyan who feels all other races are nothing more than dirt can be in-game
offensive all the want.  The moment they start persecuting specific players or
using real-world derogatories to insult people they have crossed the line.

I have been told we're not a PG-13 mud and we allow more things to occur.  To
me this means if one player calls another an ass on gossip or OOC then its not
enough to get them docked.  At most I can see us giving a warning if it
continues.

For example: Smith gossips: All orcs are assholes.

Given the standards I've been informed of, just stating this once isn't worth
even a warning.
If a second occurrence happens, a warning should occur first.
If the warning is ignored and it continues, let the docking begin.

Almost all players deserve a warning each time they start something.  If they
are repeat offenders and they're being problematic (ie doing it because they
know they'll always get warned) you can skip the warning.  If they're
problematic but have generally been behaving, a warning first is still the best
policy.

The above (about warnings) primarily applies to minor offenses.  If someone
lays in off the top with massively offensive stuff, real life racial slurring,
etc feel free to dock the appropriate amount the first time (see gsp_points,
declares 100 points) and removing the rest if they don't immediately stop.


@GDistinctions@n
Minor Foul Language: commonly heard swear words (damn, ass, fuck, etc) - 50 points
     ie: OOC god-damn I hate when that happens
     ie: OOC You asshole, stop talkin trash about my peeps
Major Foul Language: (I'm open to suggestions for specifics) - 100 points
     Real world hate mongering / Racial Slurring
       ie: OOC All [Insert Group] should die.
     Long strings of blatant profanity
       ie: OOC fuck you all, you god-damn mf bastards

Calling someone \"gay\" as a derogatory term.  Personally I'm quite offended by
this (I have quite a few \"gay\" friends) and would consider it a Major Foul
Language abuse.  Unfortunately I realize this is also common colloquial for a
lot of regions and we'll be fighting an uphill battle.  Perhaps this deserves
a warning the first time and a minor foul language offense the second?  Then
major?  I'm up for feedback on this since I'd easily just make it major on my
own.

There is also a distinction between transitory comments (something on OOC
which will scroll off and even out of OOC history soon enough) and someone
posting a note (or using title) to do something like this.  Notes and titles
are not transitory and get seen by everyone a long time or at least have the
potential too more so than chat channels do.  Violating the rules on a more
permanent forum such as this will double the penalties.

Bear in mind the target could be afk (some of our worst offenders have used
titles and they're people I've seen fall asleep at their keyboards for hours
using anti-void triggers so they don't even look particularly idle).  For
notes/titles, ask that they change it, wait, ask again (maybe dock 1 point to
get their attention and warn that they will be docked much more if they don't
respond), wait then start docking until they fix it.  If they just log off to
\"escape\" please post a note on the AV board (including succinctly the chain of
events and what you've done) so that another AV or Imm can handle them later.


Now, we all have words we find particularly offensive.  Bear in mind at all
times you are acting as a representative of the mud and not necessarily as a
person.  What sets you off may not set all people off and we have to treat it
as such.  If you can remain professional rather than personal about it, its a
lot easier to deal with people.  If someone starts pushing you buttons and you
realize you're getting personal about it (that is they stop using channels
inappropriately but are still arguing with you) try to get someone else to
deal with it rather then get drawn into an argument you're likely to hurt your
own reputation at.

Remember, as an AV, you're doing important work to keep the atmosphere of the
game consistent, fun, playable and appropriate.  If someone is abusing your
for that (ie sends you a tell stating \"Fuck You\") the moment you dock them you
have the right to dock them again.  If needed (they are a repeat offender,
commonly cause trouble, and you know they aren't likely to stop) feel free to
dock all their points and report them to an Imm to deal with.  An Imm can
validate your decision, put log notes about the trouble maker on their
account, and if necessary even reimburse docked points if the player deserves
some back.
"
