"Mob Configuration"
"This help file describes some non-obvious things you need to know when
creating mobs.


1. Flying mobs

Flying mobs are configured using the \"can_fly\" Act Mflag, and the \"fly\" Affect
Mflag.  The following lines describe what the various flag combinations mean:

!can_fly && !fly : player or mob, can't fly, always falls from air rooms.
can_fly && !fly : mob, flies only when necessary, will fall if stunned, slept, etc.
!can_fly && fly : player or mob, flies only when necessary, will never fall.
can_fly && fly : mob, always flying, will never fall.


2. Mobs and water

A mob's interaction with water is controlled by its \"swimming\" mskill level,
its \"water_breathing\" Act Mflag, and its \"water_walking\" mflag.

Definition: deep water is terrain underwater, river, or water.  It is also
terrain shallows for any mob smaller than size dog.

The water_walking flag (unlike the same affect cast on a player) will allow a
mob to leave or enter deep water.  This is useful, for example, for keeping
ducks in the pond south of chiiron...  the original TFE had it surrounded by
no_mob rooms instead.  It can also be used to prevent land animals that are
able to swim from crossing rivers when wandering.

(The water_walking affect on players acts like float, but only over water.  It
also prevents the player from swimming down into an underwater room.)

Mobs without the water_breathing affect flag will not voluntarily go
underwater, since they would drown.

Note that these mob aversions to movement are overcome when the mob becomes
someone's pet...  it will follow its leader anywhere.

Mobs with swimming mskill at zero cannot enter or leave a deep water room.

So, to create a mob that swims around the surface and never submerges, set its
swimming to nonzero, its water breathing to 0.  If you want it to be able to
leave the deep water, set its water_walking to 1.



See also: mskill, mflag.
"
