"obj_check_list"
"@eDESCRIPTION@n

This is a checklist of things to consider when creating a new object.

* Are you copying from another object, or creating from scratch?

oedit new objectname or
oedit new oldvnum objectname

* Note the vnum - you'll be using this.

* Type oset and oflag for information about the object.

* Consider the type.  See 'help object types' for more detail on each of the
possible types your object can be.

* Consider the weight.  For weapons, see help 'weapon creation.' For other
objects, set it to the appropriate weight in pounds - look at other similar
objects for ideas.

* Does the object radiate light?  Set the light field if so.  This should
usually be 0.

* How much is the object worth?  This affects repair costs as well as sale
price.

* What level is the object?  This is important for scrolls/wands/potions as
well as weapons and armor.  See the standards files again.  You'll want to
check this last.

* You can specify a number of times a player must have remorted for a player
to use the item.  If you want the equipment to be remort-only, set remort >= 1.

* If the object can be repaired, set the repair difficulty down.  10 is
impossible.  Note that obscure materials make things hard to find craftsment
for, even if the repair difficulty is low.

* If the object can be melted for a metal it contains, set the ingots field. 
Most armor should be 1 ingot, breastplates or shields can have up to 3.  For
this to work, one of the metal material flags must be set.

* [?  If the object is a gem ?], and there are other objects which are
identical when unidentified, set the fake field to the vnum of the fake
object.  See obj 998 for an example.

* Set the type-specific fields.  For example, weapons can have the damage and
type set.  Gems have quality.  Wands have charges and spells.

* Set the object's appearance fields.
Prefix_S - adjective that goes before the single object name,
Singular - noun, name of the single object. if object has unidentified name, put that in {} beforehand.
Long_S - remainder of a sentence, displayed for a single object on the ground.
Prefix_P - plural version of Prefix_S
Plural - noun, name of object when stacked. Ditto for {}
Long_S - remainder of a sentence for when stack of objects is on ground.
Before - pre-identified modifier to object name.  by default displayed before
singular/plural, but if prefixed with +, displayed after.
After - post-identified modifier to object name.  by default displayed before
singular/plural, but if prefixed with +, displayed after.
[? You can only have a particular before/after modifier appear at the start or end of the noun, not both. ?]

Example:
Prefix_S: humming
Prefix_P: resonating
( one sword is humming but if I drop two at once, I'll see 'two resonating blades...' )

Singular: {blade} daiklaive
Plural: {blades} daiklaives
( one daiklaive, two daiklaives when identified. otherwise, blade/blades. )

Long_S: is stuck into the ground here.//
Long_P: are stuck together in the ground.//
( 'A humming blade of black metal is stuck in the ground here.'
'Two resonating soulsteel daiklaives are stuck together in the ground.' )

Before: +of black metal
After: soulsteel

* Write the object's description.  Use oextra new extraname to create it, and
odesc to edit one.  'either', 'before', and 'after' are special: use
before/after for objects that vary with identification, either for ones that
don't.  This is the desc when you 'look object.' For extra details, you can
include more extras - for example, make a 'hilt' oextra, and the player can
'look sword hilt.' Objects should have a sentence at least.

Check the spelling of all oextras; after you've finished writing them, but
while still editing them, type \"odesc spell\".

* Assign suitable size oflags. This only matters for wielded/worn objects.
- custom_fit: only wearable by the person who customs it
- size_specific: only wearable by sizes flagged - also set one or more of tiny
through giant.  Players are only small through large.
- random_size: chooses random size when created.  [?  from all possible sizes
?]
- race_specific: only wearable by races flagger - also set one or more races.

* Set affect flags.  These are affects that are granted when the object is
worn.  Be careful here - look at current objects that grant that affect, and
see the standards files.

* Set object flags.  See help 'object flags' for a list.  In particular,
usually set air_fall and water_sink/float.

* Set wear flags, if you want the object to be holdable/wearable.  Unset take
if you don't want players wandering off with it.

* Set layer flags, if the object can be worn.  See help 'wear locations' and
'layer' for info on what goes where.  If in doubt, base.

* Set anti flags.  Use judgement - warriors get good armor, mages don't.  See
standards.

* set restriction flags - bladed for stuff clerics can't use, dishonorable for
paladins, no_hide for glowing things, no_sneak for noisy things.

* Set material flags.  All objects should have at least one, and often
multiple.  An object with no materials can't be repaired.

* Set object affects - oset affect for a list.  For example, for a +dam item,
oset aff dam 1.  Be careful here.

* Write object codes using opedit.

* Set object level, with all your affects and toys.

* Load one, identify it, play with it, make sure it looks right.
"
