"opset"
"@CSYNTAX@n

opset                      : shows the current action's stats
opset <field> <value>      : set action flags

@WPARAMETERS:@n

Fields that can be set are:

Trigger          : what triggers the acode being edited
Obj_Act          : set object vnum to be set to obj_act variable
Command          : used to set specific trigger commands
Target           : used to set specific targets of the Command Field

Using opset without a field will function in the same mannar as opstat.

Using opset <field> without a value will show all values available for that
field.

@CDESCRIPTION@n

The opset command is used to set the high level oprog values specific to the
object you are currently editing with oedit. Relevant help files for further
information include:
@Whelp oedit@n, @Whelp oset@n, @Whelp ostat@n, @Whelp oflag@n,
@Whelp opedit@n, @Whelp opcode@n, @Whelp opstat@n, and @Whelp oflag@n.

These values determine what triggers the opcode.  Not all the fields have to
be set. In fact, certain fields aren't even active or useful without other
fields being set correctly.

For example, oprogs set with a trigger value (usually) do not need the command
value filled.

Oprogs with the Trigger set to none can only be called from another opcode, or
when some combination of command, target and obj_act are also set.

Both the command and target fields can contain multiple options, separated by
spaces.  The Obj_Act field can contain one vnum of an object that will be used
in the processing of the opcode.

Note: The command and target fields follow the same basic rules followed in
acodes.  See @Whelp aset@n for more information.

@YDISREGARD PARAGRAPHS BELOW... OBJ_ACT IS NOT IMPLEMENTED@n

The Obj_Act field is used to check that an object is found with a matching
vnum.  The places the oprog searches are determined by the opflag command.  If
obj_act is set to some object class, and the \"target\" string is empty, and the
\"command\" string matches the user's command, the code will try to find an
object, matching the rest of the typed command string, in the room, inventory,
and worn on the player. (determined by flags set in opflag)

Note that this will consider options such as \"2.<object>\".

If the item is found, and it matches the type of object defined by Obj_Act,
the obj_act variable will be set and the oprog will be executed.  The \"obj\"
variable will be the object that the oprog is being called from, just as it is
currently.

See objects 1136 (a large walnut) and 25 (a hooded brass lantern) for examples.
"
