"Phule's Standards for Weapons"
"phule's standards for weapons.

as phule's standards for objects starts to lay out, this is in the series
of defining the level 1 baselines for weapons.

the baseline for weapons has 5 factors: type, damage weight, material,
and durability.  damage is a factor of weight, so this reduces to 4
factors.  durability is a factor of material, so we have only 3 factors:
type, material, and weight.  weight can be contradicted by two handed
weapons, and weapon type also offsets weight (4 pound staff much easier
to swing than a 4 pound sword).  also, material and weight should be able
to roughly determine the size of the object - think about density of the
metal you are working with.

For instance, the same sword made of iron and steel, the steel sword
weighs less.  so, a steel sword the same size as an iron sword, the iron
sword does more damage because it weighs more.  However the steel sword
can be swung faster, and as history will tell you, the weight of the
sword wasn't everything, after a handful of pounds, all that matters is
that it was even close to sharp and was moving fast.

Thus what we should find is that an iron sword and a steel sword should
do the SAME damage, but the steel sword will be lighter and more durable.

types:
unarmed, dagger, sword, club, staff, polearm, mace, whip, axe, bow, spear.

material:
bronze, iron, steel, mithril, adamantine.

so what we really need is a big, strange, colorful, 5-dimensional graph
plotting weapon type and material vs.  damage and weight.

what you get is...

TYPE    | WEIGHT  | DAMAGE
---------------------------------
unarmed | 0.0     | 1d4
dagger  | 1.0     | 1d8
sword   | 3.0     | 1d12
club    | 2.0     | 1d6
staff   | 3.0     | 2d4
polearm | 5.0     | 2d8
mace    | 2.5     | 2d5
whip    | 1.0     | 1d6
axe     | 3.0     | 2d6
spear   | 3.0     | 1d10
"
