"set_quest"
"@eSYNTAX@n

set_quest( ch, qnum, status )

@W@WPARAMETERS:@n

ch - pointer to character
qnum - pointer to quest involved
status - the status to set the quest to

@eDESCRIPTION@n

Sets the status of a quest on a player.
In most cases the existing quest functions should be used.  assign_quest,
has_quest, update_quest, etc.  This function, in particular, can be far more
powerful in modifying status but it can also lead to some pretty big loops
(ability to infinitely repeat quests for rewards and quest points) so be
careful with it.  This isn't a flaw, its a useful benefit if used correctly.

@W@WVALUES@n for status

-2 - Quest has been failed - use fail_quest( ch, qnum ) instead
-1 - Quest is completed - use update_quest( ch, qnum ) instead
 0 - Quest is not assigned (resets quest, can be done again)
 1 - Assigns the quest to the player - use assign_quest( ch, qnum ) instead
2+ - Useful instead of using c-flags
     These can be used to check the various steps of a quest.
     Then use get_quest( ch, # ) to see test the current quest status.

Do not use set_quest to set a value of 1, -1, or -2 unless you are absolutely
sure of what you are doing.  This function simply sets the status...  the
player receives no messages or quest points.

Note that all integer arithmetic on TFE uses 2's-complement binary with 32
bits.  So, -1 is the same as 0xffffffff, and -2 is the same as 0xfffffffe.  If
you are not careful setting specific bits in the quest value, you could end up
with a reserved value by mistake.  If in doubt, simply don't use bits 0 or 31.

**Whenever using set_quest for values other than -2, -1, 0, or 1 BE SURE TO
USE @Wqbug@n or you'll drive someone else nuts trying to figure out how the quest
works.  **

@WEXAMPLES@n

if( get_quest( ch, 100 ) == 10 ) { // player has completed stage 10 of quest #100
  set_quest( ch, 100, 11 );        // update quest to stage 11
