"Severus"
"Statements"
"This help file used to describe the structure of softcode programs on TFE, but
someone has mangled it and paraphrased it under the \"Functions\" help file.  I
wish they hadn't done that, since \"help Functions\" is now incomplete and in
some cases incorrect.
-Severus

Oh, well, starting over below. This is a work in progress.
---
A TFE softcode program is a list of zero or more @estatements@n.  Execution of the
program starts with the first statement, and proceeds sequentially.  Execution
ceases when an \"end\", \"continue\", or \"return\" statement is encountered.  If
instead the end of the program is encountered, the program terminates as if an
\"end\" statement was executed.

Line breaks and white space are not considered part of any statement.  You can
put as many statements on each line of code as you like, or you can split one
statement across multiple lines at word or punctuation boundaries.

Statements may be grouped together in @eblocks@n, which are enclosed in braces {}.
A block is considered a single statement at the level in which it appears.

Certain statements may themselves contain other statements (or blocks) whose
execution they control.  Examples of this are the \"if/else\" and \"loop\"
statements.

Below is a list of all the statements accepted by the TFE softcode parser.


@CProgram termination@n

@eend;@n


@econtinue;@n


@ereturn;@n


@CComments@n

@e// single-line comment@n

Ignored through end of line.

@e/* multiple
   line
   comment */@n

Ignored by the parser.


@CBlocks@n

@e{ <statement> [<statement> ... ] }@n
@e{ }@n

These are examples of @eblocks@n.  The second, empty block is called the \"null
statement\".


@CAssignment@n


@CFlow Control@n

@eif( <expression> )
@I<statement>
[else
@I<statement>]@n

Evaluate the expression.  If it is non-null (non-zero), execute the statement.
Otherwise, if there is an \"else\" part, execute its statement.

@eloop( <expression> )
@I<statement>@n

Evaluate the expression.  If it is non-null (non-zero), execute the statement.
Repeat.

@eloop( <macro> )
@I<statement>@n

For each element in the list represented by <macro>, execute the statement.
The values for <macro> are listed in \"help loop\".


@CFunction Calls@n


See also: expressions, functions, if-else, loop, variables.
"
