"wait("
"@CSYNTAX@n

wait( time )

@b@WPARAMETERS:@n

time - Integer number of ticks to delay

@b@WRETURNS:@n

none.

@CDESCRIPTION@n

Pauses execution of the code.  Currently, each \"tick\" is 2 seconds of real
time, corresponding to 20 seconds of imaginary \"MUD time\".

After a wait, it's always a good idea to check variables for validity before
using them.  For example:

act_tochar( #before_wait, ch );
wait( 5 );
if( ch && char_in_room( ch, room ) )
  act_tochar( #after_wait, ch );

In the code above, the if statement checks if ch is still valid, and that ch
is still in the room.

@b@RNOTE: at this time the wait() function does not operate correctly within
if/else blocks, you will have to structure your code so that the wait
statement falls outside of any blocks.  

@G// This code won'k properly.@n
@G// It will exit at the '}' if the wait is executed.@n
if( is_open( room, east ) ) {
  wait( 2 );
  act_tochar( #char, ch );
  }
act_tochar( #either, ch );

@G// This code will..@n
if( !is_open( room, east ) ) {
  act_tochar( #either, ch );
  end;
}
wait( 2 );
act_tochar( #char, ch );
act_tochar( #either, ch );

@b@RANOTHER NOTE: the \"continue\" statement will not work after a wait().@n
The wait() function call, in effect, causes an \"end\" to occur.  In an acode,
the command that caused the program to execute will stop.  After the wait, a
\"continue\" will have no effect, since the command has already been completed.

@b@WEXAMPLES:@n

wait( 1 );   // pauses for 1 tick
"
